@jaredthehawk3870 If you consent they don't need grounds or suspicion of anything. Law enforcement can order you to exit a vehicle but they need a reasonable reason to. They don't need a reason to ask you to get out of the vehicle. Once you are out, they can frisk you for weapons for their safety. Not conduct a full search. Similarly with the vehicle they can look and smell what is open to the public. That can lead to reason for a deeper search. Again nothing stops them from asking to look in your car or trunk, and how they ask can sound a lot like an order. Once they have permission they can dig around all they want until you actively remove that permission. The only way to maintain your rights is to speak them.

If they ask something of you and you don't want to, say you would rather not. Ask, is an order or request? If it is an order comply and verbally put a hard limit on it for the officer to follow the letter of the law. You give no consent, so they will have to defend their actions.

For a basic stop you have no good reason to comply with a bunch of this non-sense. They can conduct the basic needs to identify you and issue the citation. Anything past that is just extending the stop and fishing. Why do they need me out of the car or to look in the trunk for doing 42 in a 35? They don't.

